      <stem><![CDATA[<p style="">Read this excerpt from the text that includes a quotation by William Shakespeare. Then, answer the question that follows.</p><p style="">&#xA0;</p><p style="margin-left:0.5in; margin-right:0.5in; text-indent:0in; ">&#xA0;&#xA0;&#xA0;&#xA0;&#xA0;&#xA0;&#xA0;&#xA0;. . . they engage in a “<span style="text-decoration:underline; ">merry war</span> betwixt” them, in Shakespeare’s words. </p><p style="">&#xA0;</p><p style="">What is the effect of the underlined figure of speech in the text?</p>]]></stem>
      <optionlist>
        <option>
          <name>Option A</name>
          <val><![CDATA[<p style="">It mirrors the exaggeration of the claims made by Luke and Kate as they argue about the play.</p>]]></val>
          <feedback><![CDATA[<p style="">Although referring to a “friendly feud” as a war is hyperbole, that is not the figure of speech resulting from combining the words “merry” and “war.”</p>]]></feedback>
        </option>
        <option>
          <name>Option B</name>
          <val><![CDATA[<p style="">It creates irony because Beatrice and Benedick and Luke and Kate accept each other’s feelings.</p>]]></val>
          <feedback><![CDATA[<p style="">Although attributing emotions to an abstraction such as war would be an example of personification, the adjective “merry” is simply describing their “war,” not personifying it.</p>]]></feedback>
        </option>
        <option>
          <name>Option C</name>
          <val><![CDATA[<p style="">It provides a summary of the relationship between Beatrice and Benedick as well as Luke and Kate.</p>]]></val>
          <feedback><![CDATA[<p style="">CORRECT. “Merry war” is an oxymoron because the concepts contradict each other, but it describes the “long-running but friendly feud” between the two sets of characters: those in the play and those in the text.</p>]]></feedback>
        </option>
        <option>
          <name>Option D</name>
          <val><![CDATA[<p style="">It makes the bitter anger between Beatrice and Benedick seem less harsh, just as Luke is trying to do.</p>]]></val>
          <feedback><![CDATA[<p style="">Although the words do not say exactly what is meant (because they are an example of figurative language), they are not covering up or mitigating a harsh meaning like a euphemism, but mirroring a multi-faceted relationship.</p>]]></feedback>
        </option>
      </optionlist>
